      <div xml:id="NA279-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu makaṭ pōkkiya tāy colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the mother said who had let [her] daughter go.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA279">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vēmpi ṉoṇpaḻa muṇaii yiruppait</l>
<l>            tēmpāl ceṟṟa tīmpaḻa ṉacaii</l>
<l>            vaikupaṉi yuḻanta vāval ciṉaitoṟu</l>
<l>            neytōy tiriyiṟ ṟaṇcita ruṟaippa</l>
<l>            nāṭcura muḻanta vāṭkē ḻēṟṟaiyoṭu </l>
<l>            poruta yāṉaip puṭṭā ḷēyppap</l>
<l>            pacipiṭi yutaitta vōmaic cevvarai</l>
<l>            veyilkā yamaiyat timaikku mattat</l>
<l>            tataruḻan tacaiyiṉa kollō tataralvāyc</l>
<l>            cilampu kaḻīiya celvam </l>
<l>            piṟaruḻaik kaḻintaveṉ ṉāyiḻai yaṭiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Did they become weary, bearing the fine sand</l>
<l rend="indent">on the route, where the red trunk of the Ōmai tree,</l>
<l rend="indent">kicked by the hungry she-elephant, twinkles at the time the sunlight is hot,</l>
<l rend="indent2">resembling the wounded leg of an elephant that was beaten</l>
<l rend="indent2">by the male of bright lustrous [stripes] that has borne the desert by day,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when cool dew drips like a wick soaked in ghee</l>
<l rend="indent3">on every branch [full of]<note place="foot">Actually, there is neither a syntactical nor a topological link which would allow us to connect the description of the fruit bats in the first three lines with that of the tiger-elephant fight in the next lines. Do they really belong here?</note> bats that bore the tarrying dew,</l>
<l rend="indent4">hating the bright fruits of the Neem [and] yearning for</l>
<l rend="indent4">the sweet fruits subdued(?) in honey milk of the Iruppai,</l>
<l>– the feet of my [girl of] choice jewels who passed into being close to others,</l>
<l rend="indent">[who have]<note place="foot">Syntax and meaning of the last two lines are illusive. What is the relation of <term xml:lang="ta">piṟar uḻai</term> to <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻinta</term>, and how to connect the celvam of the previous line?</note> the fortune of removing [her] anklets,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[their] mouths being squashed?<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tataral vāy</term> is a problem here. Since tataral is elsewhere (cf. KT 213.3) used as a metaphorical expression for "bark", T.V.G. wants to connect it here with the bark peeled off the tree by the female elephant, but this seems syntactically impossible. I suggest to read it as an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">cilampu</term>, referring to the fact that this girl’s anklets have to be broken in order to remove them.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
